":"英國","Owlton, Durham, England":"英國達勒姆","lifeSummary":"當William Lambert於1272年之前出生在英國達勒姆時，他的父親Thomas Lambert11268歲，母親Margaret de Calverley34歲。他和Jane Cresey至少有1個兒子。他去世於大約1307年之後。"},"zh-hans":{"Bef 1272–after about 1307":"1272年之前–大约1307年之后","1272–1307":"1272年–1307年","1276–Female":"1276年–殁","1307–1360":"1307年–1360年","1216–1279":"1216年–1279年","1237–Female":"1237年–殁","1216":"1216年","Bef 1272":"1272年之前","after about 1307":"大约1307年之后","1237":"1237年","1279":"1279年","1276":"1276年","about 1300":"大约1300年","1360":"1360年","1272":"1272年","1307":"1307年","1290":"1290年","Durham, England":"英国英格兰達勒姆達勒姆","England":"英国","Owlton, Durham, England":"英国達勒姆","lifeSummary":"当William Lambert于1272年之前出生在英国達勒姆时，他的父亲Thomas Lambert11268岁，母亲Margaret de Calverley34岁。他和Jane Cresey至少有1个儿子。他去世于大约1307年之后。"},"hr":{"Bef 1272–after about 1307":"prije 1272.–otprilike nakon 1307.","1272–1307":"1272–1307.","1276–Female":"1276–preminula","1307–1360":"1307.–1360","1216–1279":"1216–1279.","1237–Female":"1237–preminula","1216":"1216","Bef 1272":"prije 1272.","after about 1307":"otprilike nakon 1307.","1237":"1237","1279":"1279.","1276":"1276","about 1300":"oko 1300.","1360":"1360","1272":"1272","1307":"1307.","1290":"1290","Durham, England":"Durham, Durham, Engleska, United Kingdom","England":"England","Owlton, Durham, England":"Durham, England"},"cs":{"Bef 1272–after about 1307":"před 1272–po okolo 1307","1272–1307":"1272–1307","1276–Female":"1276–Zesnulá","1307–1360":"1307–1360","1216–1279":"1216–1279","1237–Female":"1237–Zesnulá","1216":"1216","Bef 1272":"před 1272","after about 1307":"po okolo 1307","1237":"1237","1279":"1279","1276":"1276","about 1300":"okolo 1300","1360":"1360","1272":"1272","1307":"1307","1290":"1290","Durham, England":"Durham, Durham, Anglie, United Kingdom","England":"Anglie","Owlton, Durham, England":"Durham, Anglie"},"da":{"Bef 1272–after about 1307":"før 1272–efter omkring 1307","1272–1307":"1272–1307","1276–Female":"1276–Afdød","1307–1360":"1307–1360","1216–1279":"1216–1279","1237–Female":"1237–Afdød","1216":"1216","Bef 1272":"før 1272","after about 1307":"efter omkring 1307","1237":"1237","1279":"1279","1276":"1276","about 1300":"omkring 1300","1360":"1360","1272":"1272","1307":"1307","1290":"1290","Durham, England":"Durham, Durham, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Owlton, Durham, England":"Durham, England"},"nl":{"Bef 1272–after about 1307":"vóór 1272–na circa 1307","1272–1307":"1272–1307","1276–Female":"1276–Overleden","1307–1360":"1307–1360","1216–1279":"1216–1279","1237–Female":"1237–Overleden","1216":"1216","Bef 1272":"vóór 1272","after about 1307":"na circa 1307","1237":"1237","1279":"1279","1276":"1276","about 1300":"circa 1300","1360":"1360","1272":"1272","1307":"1307","1290":"1290","Durham, England":"Durham, Durham, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England","Owlton, Durham, England":"Durham, England"},"en":{"Bef 1272–after about 1307":"before 1272–after about 1307","1272–1307":"1272–1307","1276–Female":"1276–Deceased","1307–1360":"1307–1360","1216–1279":"1216–1279","1237–Female":"1237–Deceased","1216":"1216","Bef 1272":"before 1272","after about 1307":"after about 1307","1237":"1237","1279":"1279","1276":"1276","about 1300":"about 1300","1360":"1360","1272":"1272","1307":"1307","1290":"1290","Durham, England":"Durham, Durham, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Owlton, Durham, England":"Durham, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lambert","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, French, Walloon, Dutch, German, Polish, Czech, and Slovak: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>land</i> ‘land, territory’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. In England, the native Old English form <i>Landbeorht</i> was replaced by <i>Lambert</i>, the Continental form of the name that was taken to England by the Normans from France. The name gained wider currency in Britain in the Middle Ages with the immigration of weavers from Flanders, among whom Saint Lambert or Lamprecht, bishop of Maastricht in around 700, was a popular cult figure. In Italy the name was popularized in the Middle Ages as a result of the fame of Lambert I and II, Dukes of Spoleto and Holy Roman Emperors. <i>Lambert</i> is the second most frequent surname in Wallonia. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, for example Slovenian <b>Lampret</b> and <b>Lampreht</b> (see also   Lampert  ).","History: Aubin Lambert <i>dit</i> Champagne from Tourouvre in Orne, France, married Élisabeth Aubert in Quebec City, QC, in 1670; see also   Champagne  . Eustache Lambert from Boulogne-sur-Mer in Pas-de-Calais, France, married Marie Laurence in France <i>c.</i> 1656, died in Quebec City, QC, in 1673. Pierre Lambert from Fourmetot in Eure, France, married Marie Normand in Quebec City, QC, in 1680. Augustin Hébert <i>dit</i> Lambert, a descendant of Augustin Hébert from Paris, France, married Françoise Petit in Varennes, QC, in 1761. — This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of America."],"variants":[{"name":"Lambers","meanings":["Dutch: patronymic from the personal name   Lambert  ."]},{"name":"Lamberth","meanings":["English: variant of   Lambert  ."]},{"name":"Lambertus","meanings":["German and Dutch: humanistic name, Latinized form of the personal name   Lambert  ."]},{"name":"Lamberti","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Antonio, Carlo, Gaetano, Luciano, Amedeo, Angelo, Biagio, Domenic, Donato, Enrico, Gino, Iolanda.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of the personal name <i>Lamberto</i>, an equivalent of   Lambert  . This surname is also found in Corsica and southern France.","German and Dutch: Latinized (humanistic) patronymic from the personal name   Lambert  , using the genitive of its Latinized form   Lambertus  ."]},{"name":"Lamberty","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Ana, Dimas, Jose, Juan, Altagracia, Angel, Blanca, Efrain, Fernando, Jaime, Ramon.","German and French: Latinized (humanistic) patronymic from the personal name   Lambert  , from <i>Lamberti</i>, the genitive of its Latinized form   Lambertus  . Compare   Lamberti   2."]},{"name":"Lambertz","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Heinz, Erna, Johann, Ralf.","North German: patronymic from   Lambert  ."]},{"name":"Lamberto","meanings":["Italian and Spanish: from the personal name <i>Lamberto</i> (see   Lambert  )."]},{"name":"Lampert","meanings":["English, North German, Dutch, and Slovak; Hungarian (<b>Lampért</b>): variant of   Lambert  . In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed some cognates from other languages, for example Slovenian <b>Lampret</b> and <b>Lampreht</b>.","English: variant of <b>Lambard</b>, an occupational name from Middle English <i>lambherd</i>, <i>lambhird</i>, <i>lambhurd</i> ‘lamb-herd’ (Old English <i>lamb</i> + <i>hierde</i>)."]},{"name":"Lambertsen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik.","Dutch, Danish, North German, and Norwegian: patronymic from the personal name   Lambert  . This surname has died out in the Netherlands.","History: Cornelius Lambertsen came from Utrecht, the Netherlands, arriving at New Amsterdam in New Netherland (now New York City, NY) in 1642."]},{"name":"Lamb","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Lamb</i>, a pet form of   Lambert  .","English: nickname for a meek and inoffensive person, from Middle English <i>lamb</i>, or a metonymic occupational name for a keeper of lambs. See also   Lamm  .","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Luain</b> ‘descendant of the warrior’, formerly Anglicized as <b>O'Loan</b> (see   Lane   3). MacLysaght comments: \"The form <b>Lamb(e)</b>, which results from a more than usually absurd pseudo-translation (<i>uan</i> ‘lamb’), is now much more numerous than <i>O'Loan</i> itself.\"."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":18,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When William Lambert was born before 1272, in Durham, England, his father, Thomas Lambert, was 11268 and his mother, Margaret de Calverley, was 34. He had at least 1 son with Jane Cresey. He died after about 1307."},"et":{"Bef 1272–after about 1307":"enne 1272–umbes pärast 1307","1272–1307":"1272–1307","1276–Female":"1276–Surnud","1307–1360":"1307–1360","1216–1279":"1216–1279","1237–Female":"1237–Surnud","1216":"1216","Bef 1272":"enne 1272","after about 1307":"umbes pärast 1307","1237":"1237","1279":"1279","1276":"1276","about 1300":"umbes 1300","1360":"1360","1272":"1272","1307":"1307","1290":"1290","Durham, England":"Durham, Durham, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Owlton, Durham, England":"Durham, England"},"fi":{"Bef 1272–after about 1307":"ennen vuotta 1272–noin 1307 jälkeen","1272–1307":"1272–1307","1276–Female":"1276–Kuollut","1307–1360":"1307–1360","1216–1279":"1216–1279","1237–Female":"1237–Kuoll